[13/4 AR] CLOSED RP - /RU Corp Interview Station, SRA 3701522.180784498M | The /RU Corporation's selected Tenno applicants arrive at an isolated space station for their interviews, but they find it decrepit and locked.
Disruptis - Disruptis 25-Aug-18 04:26 PM
It is said that if you stand on the atmosphere-stripped moon, one can easily witness the many colours of the observable galaxy dance upon the night sky. The empty space is a perfect medium in revealing everything in its inky grasp. However, the black between still manages to hide many things to this day. One of them is a small space station, floating far from the view of any planet or moon. You would never find it unless you were looking for it, and knew where it was. Now, some Tenno, their fortune or lack thereof soon to be determined, are aiming to enter its hidden halls. These selected Tenno, whom had recently applied to work for the Corporation, received a follow-up message within 48 hours.
--/RU Recruitment Services Salutations! After reviewing your application we have decided to select you for our interviewing process. Please visit the coordinates attached on 29/21 OS at exactly 15:00. It is important that you arrive on time. We look forward to working with you. :) SRA: 22h 26m 28.0s 19.23ms 72.01μs SDec: -10° 10’ 12.8’’ 3.6’’’ 1.2’’’’ SDis: 3701522.180784498M
. . . ..... (edited)
[AR 13/4] A myriad of lights flickered in the darkness of space. Any way of looking into cold structure they thrived upon was blocked by tightly shut blinds: the eyelids of a sleeping giant. Well, not a giant exactly. In fact, it was quite small. Suspiciously so. Shards of metal upon its exterior cut outwards into the inky black at odd angles. They were accompanied by doors exposed to the vacuum of space, seething with burning red lights. Despite this, the lonely station’s clean Corpus design strangely showed no beatings from the outside. Tall flood lamps stood upon a flat, empty protrusion of the building, presumably a drop-off zone, as they fought valiantly against the overwhelming atmosphere of eeriness around it. Perhaps in some eyes they had failed their mission, only serving to spread the uneasiness further. Fortunately for them, demons hardly bat an eye to such darkness, and demons were exactly the visitors they were now expecting. Well again, demons and two… ah… you’ll see. A small entranceway room was constructed in its center against the wall and stood as the only way of getting inside. It too, was locked for the moment. But unlike most of the station, its windows were not obstructed, allowing a peek into its unlit interior. (edited)

Prophet-Scott 25-Aug-18 06:21 PM
Zereth Zereth dashed at the best of his ability to avoid one of the relentless blade-swings of the simulation droid. With a graceful spin he disarmed one of the drones, slicing its arm clean off with his Nikana. Zereth thrusted his hand forward, directing his fingers into a tight clenching motion. Void energy started pulsing around his hand, reflecting in his golden gaze. He'd raise his hand, lifting the droid off of its legs and with a forceful swing with his arm the dismembered droid was encapsuled with void energy, flinging him with an immense force into another training droid. Another one of the agile droids doomed up from behind, twisting him around and punching him in the gut. The droid was about to swing its training sword before the simulation was paused, and the scenery started dematerializing into the trianing simulator room. Cephalon Eldar: "I'm sorry to interrupt your training session, starchild. But I have good news! You've received a message in your inbox, I believe it is from the organization you applied for." Zereth grabbed his stomach, getting up from his knees, patting the droid on it's shoulder. "Next time I'll get you Z-4." He'd grunt a bit, trying to mask the pain his gut was experiencing right now. "Eldar, read the message." (edited)
(1/2) (edited)
The cephalon obeyed the command and with pride read the received message. "Isn't that great starchild? You've been chosen! I expect nothing less from our prodigy." Zereth's lips curled up to a smirk whilst he took off his training suit and replaced it for one of his nice, flowing white robes. His feet tapped over the heated orbiter flooring while he brought his finger to his lower lip. "How interesting. I've been looking for some run-ins with the unknown. Undiscovered means unclaimed. Eldar, set course for the provided coordinates and ready my landing craft. We've got a deadline to catch. Oh- and fill a hot bath for me will you?" He said, whilst wandering into his personal quarters. He took a moment to look at his own reflection in one of his many ayatan treasures before looking at one of his displayed warframes. It was his Harrow. "I believe its time you get another run, good friend." He said valiantly looking at the golden-trimmed, completely black frame. "Consider it done, star child." Eldar replied to his requests. The sound of the Orbiter's engines started roaring, taking a few minutes to start up. Zereth made his way to his bathing chamber, disrobing and sinking into his bath, groaning at the feeling of his stomach. He'd tilt his head back as the feeling subsided, smirking at his lapis lazuli sealing, looking at the golden constellations displayed on it. “How thrilling. Here we come. Eldar, engage hyperjump.” At that instant the ship hyper-drive engines bursted forth an immense amount of energy, warping them to close proximity of their destination. (2/2) (edited)

Ross 25-Aug-18 07:13 PM
Kinsey Kinsey sat on the floor of their cluttered orbiter, using a screwdriver to scrape greasy Kubrow hair out of the latch mechanism to their personal quarters. A scanner tuned to local Grineer frequencies played loudly from elsewhere in the ship as it made another lazy orbit around Mars. Once they deemed the door clear of any more clumps of hair, they stood and brushed themself off with grubby hands, tossing the screwdriver in the vague direction of their foundry. The scanner's volume suddenly sank as Kinsey's cephalon spoke. "Operator, you have a response to your application. I think it's a bad idea but you've had worse so I'm not stopping you." Kinsey sighed dramatically. "Rahm, Vilkas! Just read the message!" The Tenno set about re-organizing one of their scrap piles while Vilkas recited the message. Tossing a ration pack into the proper pile, they straightened. "Wait, did the message really have a smiley in it?" "Believe it or not, yes." "Huh. Weirdos. Well, go to the coordinates, then. I'd rather get there on time." Vilkas gave an affirmative beep, and the engines sputtered to life as Kinsey wandered to their quarters to fetch their favorite warframe. No inch of wall space was unclaimed, countless portraits of grineer defectors displayed throughout the room. Oddly, the portraits of two Corpus crewmen occupied a section of their own, looking out of place among the countless identical, warped faces. An alcove in the center of the wall boasted the form of a battered white Frost with orange detailing, posed with an Ack and Brunt at the ready. "Alright, frosty boy, let's get going. Here's hoping I'm not the only one to show up, eh?" they chattered to their warframe as they selected an option on a yellow-tinted screen, causing the platform to lower the warframe to the ground. With a rush of void energy, the tenno transferred into the warframe, and Leveret stepped forward, rolling his shoulders. (1/2)
Leveret The doors to his quarters closed behind him with a hiss - nice, it's working now - and he made his way to the front of the orbiter. On his way forward, the entire ship lurched as it picked up speed in preparation to travel to the given coordinates. Leveret, quite used to the jolt, didn't even pause in his steps. He sat unceremoniously on a crate at the front of the ship, watching his favorite red planet fade quickly from view. Tucking one leg under himself in a half-assed approximation of a meditative position, Leveret settled in to watch the stars as he approached his destination. (2/2)

Daakjenaar 25-Aug-18 11:59 PM
KAMOS The sunlight reflected off the silver plating on the Rhino as he trudged through the undergrowth of one of Earth's many forests. He always came here to relax. Somewhere out of the way of the chaos of the rest of the system. The Liset that had brought him here hovered just above the ground, safe from the wildlife on the ground. Boarding the ship, Kamos flew the ship back to orbit. And, of course, his inbox was full of new messages. Spam, spam, wrong person, ghouls again... Oh, hey. A message from RU. It's about time. "So, Atela, these RU guys accepted me. That means I'll probably be moving around a lot more. When you're able to respond to my messages, I'll probably be allowed to tell you where I am." Kamos stepped away from the recording device, letting the message send to his partner in crime. He hasn't heard from her for months. She was probably still busy with her mission. He wasn't entirely sure what she was doing, but it was probably important, right? Kamos input the provided coordinates, and let the Orbiter pilot itself there. He went about wandering around the ship, as he often did lately. It felt a bit more empty without Atela, but that wasn't too bad. More space for his noggles, then. Noggles were great. The footsteps of the Rhino echoed throughout the ship rhythmically, as he checked for anything out of order. Nothing, as always. Everything was always in order.

Amidst the inky blackness of space, a Liset sped towards the secluded space station. The craft's engines began to taper off as it neared the obvious, if rather off-putting landing platform, which at present sat empty, save for a single, emerald-colored craft. As the craft finished docking, the craft's door opened with a hiss. Aurelia: She had come a long way for this... "Interview." She happened upon the signal by chance, but the voice that came with the message had grabbed her attention with the intensity of a black hole. 'It couldn't be him', she had thought at the time. They were dead. Everyone was dead. But the voice was too enticing for her to ignore. She scanned the immediate area cautiously, unconvinced that she wasn't walking into a trap. Finding no apparent threats, she sent her little puppet forward, its metallic feet clicking onto the landing pad. It was a small drone of Corpus design: a MOA, albeit one that was altered for reconnaissance rather than combat. It's blue paint job seemed to glow in the stark light as it purposefully strode towards the waiting door. If she was right, then she would have excellent news to report to her Operator. If she was wrong... Well, one MOA would be an acceptable loss.

Nor_Urzak - Muro/Aurelia 06-Sep-18 12:36 AM
Aurelia: This landing pad had certainly gotten more lively, with three more Tenno now arriving on the platform. While Aurelia was grateful to have the rather exuberant Tenno from earlier distracted with the new arrivals, she didn't feel any more at ease with the current crowd present. If this was indeed a trap of some sort, whoever was responsible for setting it up must have been quite confident if they thought they could take on this many Tenno at once, even if some of them did not appear to be fully armed. By her reasoning, this presented three likely scenarios: first, this interview was indeed genuine, which would be a welcome turn of events, she admitted to herself. Second, this was indeed a setup, but their host was overconfident in their abilities to hold multiple Tenno, much less kill them. Thinking from her own memory, even a small group of uncoordinated Tenno was capable of decimating thousands of soldiers and mechanical proxies with seemingly little difficulty. Finally, there was the third option: This was a trap, and their host was someone who was actually capable of subduing that many Tenno. The last possibility made Aurelia shudder apprehensively. There was a short list of people throughout the system that she was aware of that could be capable of that. None of them were people Aurelia would enjoy interacting with. All the same, two of the Tenno being apparently good friends was a good sign to her, as that would likely reduce the overall tension of the meeting. Speaking of which... Aurelia offered the closest thing the MOA could manage to a bow, dipping its muzzle downward towards the rather polite Mirage frame for a moment before turning back to the entrance to the larger station and directing the MOA to move in that direction. Standing out here would provide no answers as to what awaited inside.
